# Enterprise Multi-Agent AI Platform - Detailed Problem Statement

## Background

We are designing a next-generation enterprise AI platform for a large financial institution.

The platform performs document processing, policy validation, compliance checks, quality assurance, risk analysis and other enterprise workflows using multiple AI agents.

This platform must satisfy enterprise-grade security requirements expected in banking environments while remaining scalable enough to expose individual AI capabilities as standalone enterprise products in the future.

The objective is to design a modern, production-ready, zero-trust architecture that balances:

- Security
- Scalability
- Performance
- Governance
- Auditability
- Operational simplicity
- Future extensibility

The solution should be realistic using technologies available in 2026.

---

# Existing Architecture

Current architecture follows a Supervisor-Agent pattern.

```
External Client
      │
      ▼
Supervisor Agent
      │
 ┌────┼────┐
 │    │    │
 ▼    ▼    ▼
OCR  Policy Quality
```

Characteristics:

- Single supervisor exposed externally
- Supervisor invokes downstream agents
- Agents cannot communicate directly
- Internal communication occurs inside same VPC
- ARN/internal identity assumptions
- Minimal authentication between internal agents
- Shared trust boundary
- Workflow execution handled by Supervisor

Initially this architecture is simple and efficient.

However the organization expects the platform to evolve into an enterprise marketplace where each agent becomes independently consumable.

Future architecture:

```
External Client
        │
        ├─────────────► OCR Agent
        ├─────────────► Policy Agent
        ├─────────────► Quality Agent
        └─────────────► Risk Agent
```

Each agent becomes its own reusable enterprise capability.

---

# Major Business Requirement

Each agent must eventually become independently callable.

Example:

Different internal products may only require OCR.

Other teams may only require Policy validation.

External partners may only require Risk Assessment.

Therefore every agent must support:

- independent invocation
- independent scaling
- independent deployment
- independent authorization
- independent ownership
- independent lifecycle

Agents should become reusable enterprise services.

---

# New Design Philosophy

Instead of a central Supervisor Agent making intelligent routing decisions, the platform should use a deterministic workflow engine.

The workflow engine should only coordinate execution.

It should never contain business intelligence.

It should never behave like an AI agent.

Its responsibilities include:

- sequencing
- retries
- compensation
- state management
- approval gates
- timeout handling
- orchestration logic

Business intelligence remains inside individual agents.

---

# Critical Design Constraints

## 1. No Agent-to-Agent Communication

Agents must never call other agents.

Example:

BAD

OCR
  │
  ▼
Policy
  │
  ▼
Quality

GOOD

Workflow Engine

calls

OCR

then

Workflow Engine

calls

Policy

then

Workflow Engine

calls

Quality

Each agent only talks to:

- Workflow Engine
- API Gateway
- Approved enterprise services

Never another agent.

---

## 2. No Shared Memory

Agents must not access shared memory.

No global memory store.

No shared conversation context.

No shared vector database accessible by every agent.

Each request should contain everything the agent requires.

---

## 3. Stateless Agents

Agents should be stateless.

Any workflow state belongs to Workflow Engine.

Any memory belongs to external state storage.

Agents simply receive input and return output.

Example:

Input

JSON

↓

Agent

↓

JSON

No hidden internal state.

---

## 4. JSON-only Communication

Agents should return structured JSON.

No free-form inter-agent conversations.

Example

OCR returns

{
 "text":"..."
}

Policy returns

{
 "violations":[...]
}

Quality returns

{
 "score":94
}

Workflow engine consumes JSON outputs.

---

## 5. Zero Trust

Assume every component can eventually become compromised.

Trust nothing.

Every request must authenticate independently.

Every request must authorize independently.

Every request must be validated independently.

Being inside a VPC is NOT sufficient trust.

